Title: Rewiring Your Mind for AI: How to Think, Work, and Thrive in the Age of Intelligence
Author: David                     Wood
My Review:
What sets this book apart is its range:
• If you’re new to AI, it gives you the language to confidently enter the conversation.
• If you’re already deep in the space, it sharpens your thinking and challenges assumptions you didn’t even realize you held.

As an engineer who is actively building with AI, I came in expecting a light or familiar read. Instead, I found a deeply thought-provoking framework for engaging with AI more intentionally.

David Wood doesn’t just explain how AI works; rather, he helps you rethink how you think.

The paradigm-shifting mindset that “AI Is Not Google” (Chapter 3) is especially timely. It’s easy to just treat AI like an answer vending machine, when it carries the potential to empower “beginners to do the impossible” (Chapter 5).

So I’m recommending this book to anyone and everyone. I genuinely believe AI is reshaping society faster than most people realize, and this book is a cheat code for those who want to stay ahead of the curve.

Title: Built to Move: The Ten Essential Habits to Help You Move Freely and Live Fully
Author: Kelly Starrett
My Review:
Built to Move was one of those rare, paradigm-shifting reads that immediately challenged what I thought I knew about fitness and caused me to rethink and reframe. The authors make a compelling case that our sedentary culture is slowly eroding our health—even for those of us who exercise regularly. As they put it:

“Props to you for working out, but it’s not the same as moving your body throughout the day in all the healthy ways it’s hardwired to move.”

That hit home for me. I’ve fallen into the trap of thinking a solid run in the morning makes up for long hours sitting at a desk. This book challenged that mindset in a way that felt both empowering and actionable.

I also appreciated their nuanced view of fitness:

“If you want to see how good your fitness regimen is... see if you can move capably across platforms.”

In other words, functional fitness isn’t about crushing your favorite routine—it’s about being able to move well in any environment.

I thought I was fit because I run marathons, but the Ten Vital Signs opened my eyes to some glaring deficiencies in range of motion and functional strength. Since reading this book, I’ve started walking more throughout the day, adding weightlifting to my routine, and carving out time for regular mobility work. I'm grateful this book came into my orbit and I'm sure I'll refer to it many more times.

Title: The 48 Laws of Power
Author: Robert Greene
My Review:
I’ve seen The 48 Laws of Power on recommended reading lists for years and finally decided to read it. And it was diabolical. I fundamentally disagree with its Machiavellian premise that life is merely a quest for power and that deceit, cruelty, and manipulation are essential tools for success.

Admittedly, it was eye-opening and intriguing to consider how power-obsessed leaders in history (or in current times) may perceive the world. But my main problem with this book is that it is not written as an exploration on the concept of power, it is written as an often ruthless manual for obtaining power above all else which I find to be dangerous and misleading as a singular goal.

I also personally find unconvincing the argument that this book is still valuable for understanding how others might wield power against us. If I choose to believe that these laws truly do govern the world, then I have to sacrifice my trust in relationships, morality, and humanity. And that is too steep of a cost.
Private Notes: It only took me a few pages into the preface to realize that I fundamentally disagree with the thesis of the book which made it difficult to read with an open mind. Admittedly, there might be truth in some of these ideas, but that makes the book feel even more dangerous if read as a manual for success (which is how it is written). Following these "laws" may result in obtaining more power but is that really worth the cost of sacrificing all morality, relationships, and humanity? Maximus > Commodus

Title: Nexus: A Brief History of Information Networks from the Stone Age to AI
Author: Yuval Noah Harari
My Review:
While Nexus doesn’t quite reach the heights of "21 Lessons for the 21st Century", it remains a worthwhile read for its historical and political context on the evolving landscape of information and artificial intelligence—what Harari provocatively rebrands as "alien intelligence".

One of the most compelling sections for me was Chapter 4, "Errors," where Harari challenges the naive view of information: the belief that if we accumulate enough data, it will naturally converge to truth. He writes, "Contrary to the naive view, information has no essential link to truth... Its defining feature is connection rather than representation." Historically, information networks have often prioritized social order and power over truth.

Harari emphasizes that for networks to prioritize truth over falsehood, they must develop strong self-correcting mechanisms. He highlights how scientific institutions excel at this because they are not only willing to admit error and ignorance—they are actively incentivized to expose them. In contrast, the absence of such mechanisms in early modern Europe allowed the witch hunts to spiral into mass hysteria and false narratives.

At times, the book leans too heavily into a cynical, doomsday tone for my taste, but it did open my eyes to some potential scenarios I had never considered and caused me to temper my optimism somewhat around the advancements in AI.

Title: Hunting For Happiness: The Outdoorsman's guide to getting rid of buck fever, cowboying up and enjoying life.
Author: Zack Butterfield
My Review:
One of the most accessible and interesting books I’ve read on the topic of happiness and self-improvement. While targeted towards rural communities, its lessons and stories resonate universally. As someone who doesn’t hunt, I still found the animal-centered stories and analogies captivating, offering a fresh and powerful perspective on mental health. Butterfield illustrates how we, as humans, are animals ourselves—and how self-destructive behaviors emerge when we fail to recognize and address our primitive (and often buried) emotions.

The book’s structure is a standout: each chapter explores a mental health topic with a creative title (such as "Deer in the Headlights" or "Finding Your Herd"), ties it to an experience from the author’s life with animals, shares a real-life client story from his therapy sessions, and provides practical, science-based advice for the reader.

Overall, it is a quick and engaging read but packs a punch of insightful lessons. Highly recommended.

Title: The Anxious Generation: How the Great Rewiring of Childhood Caused an Epidemic of Mental Illness
Author: Jonathan Haidt
My Review:
Haidt's central claim of the book is that we are overprotecting our children in the real world while underprotecting them online. Despite alarming statistics, I appreciated that the author maintained an optimistic tone by providing concrete ways parents, educators, and governments can act to reverse these trends.

Four foundational reforms:
1. No smartphones before high school
2. No social media before 16
3. Phone-free schools
4. Far more unsupervised play and childhood independence

I hope that this well-written, compelling book will bring these ideas into the mainstream.
